Recording Academy has announced that the 2022 Grammy Awards has been rescheduled for April 2, 2022 after initial postponement. The Nation had reported that the event, which was formerly slated to hold on January 31st, was postponed due to the rise in COVID-19 variant, Omicron. Chief Executive Officer of the Recording Academy, Harvey Mason, made this known in a statement. He also revealed that the event which was usually held in Los Angeles will take place in Las Vegas for the first time. The statement reads: “I’m so pleased to let you know that the 64th Annual GRAMMY Awards have been rescheduled and will now be broadcast live from the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas on Sunday.   Anita Joseph to marriage critics: you will sink first     Wizkid, Tiwa Savage, others battle for 2022 NAACP Awards     Tiwa savage’s sex video appears in examination…   - Advertisement - “We are excited to take the GRAMMYs to Las Vegas for the very first time and to put on a world-class show. From the moment we announced the postponement of the original show date, we have been inundated with heartfelt messages of support and solidarity from the artist community. “We are humbled by their generosity and grateful for their unwavering commitment to the GRAMMY Awards and the Academy’s mission.” South African comedian, Trevor Noah, who hosted the 63rd edition of the Grammy will play Master of Ceremonies for the second time at the event. The Grammy Awards, which had been postponed due to the Covid-19 pandemic, have been rescheduled for April 3 in Las Vegas,